From Craig Powderkeg DeForest Subject Re Need advice for riding with someone on pillion In article Bob Wert writes I need some advice on having someone ride pillion with me on my This will be the the first time I've taken anyone for an extended ride read farther than around the block We'll be riding some twisty fairly bumpy roads the Mines Road Loop for you SF Bay Areans Communication work out your own Or just slow down and holler back every once in a At reasonable speeds even on my under muffled Magna we can hear each It's only above say MPH that you can't really Balance New passengers are a real pain because you never know how they're going to react to Some people catch on immediately and lean with Others are completely skittish about the leaning thing and keep their bodies perpendicular to the This is a pain while turning but The WORST are the passengers who stay perpendicular to the horizon then REMEMBER in the middle of a turn and WHIP AROUND until they're in the correct' This always screws up the line I've picked Here's my personal checklist of things to tell passengers attire helmet long pants boots heavy shoes Keep feet on pegs at all times unless I say Do not get on off unless I say you I've had people try to dismount in traffic just as I'm pulling in to a parking space Muffler gets HOT 'Nuff said We get GOOD We're not going to fall Many first time riders are surprised by how tightly you can turn Turn dynamics sit so that you feel like you're sitting upright and we're going Trust your butt not your eyes if you're confused close your eyes for a couple of turns to get the feel of Or just hug me Please no sudden moves shift your weight as desired but be gradual so I can Your faceplate is yours to open close as Trust is Trust the driver me to do the right thing I've driven many miles on this thing and know how to operate Enjoy the This is important to For example one of my first time passwngers seemed to watch the speedo like a hawk I drove her to the beach down and whever we topped mph she'd holler SLOW DOWN I'M SCARED I humored her for a while then simply covered the speedometer with the spare piece of duct tape I keep stuck to the top of the Problem solved she watched the scenery instead of the instruments and had a much better Based on her experience driving a Lincoln Continental she was unwilling to trust my ability to choose a safe speed for the Usually I'll point out the controls engine transmission brakes tires and discuss motorcycle physics a bit too for first Helps calm their nerves and gives the bike a chance to warm Watch out for gravel on the Hamilton road there were lots of little mudslides after the last big rain by now many of the blind corners will be nicely covered with a carpet of little round nearly invisible It doesn't help build trust when you slide out on a blind corner on the first trip Good luck have fun DON'T DRINK SOAP DILUTE DILUTE OK